\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5600746 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 Did going to work change your attitude to life at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 No, it didn't change any attitude, only - you - you wanted - you wanted get higher than what you o
riginally was you see. You - if you saw anybody - getting something as you weren't getting you didn't like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5600746 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 You still lived at home after you started work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 I - And it made you as you - a little bit jealous of him because he was getting - more up the ladder than you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5600746 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 Did starting work change your attitude to your sister or brother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 No. No. The change - she - she were working as well as me you know and I told you she were a gasser didn't I.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5600746 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 Did you still go to Sunday school or church when you left school and went towork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 Oh yes, we went to Sunday school. But - we had misses in between, we didn't go regular.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5600746 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 Did you take an interest in politics when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 No more than - just going wit' to the lads you 
know when they were - when you had blue ribbon or - a yellow ribbon, Labour, or anything - no more than that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5600746 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 You weren't interested in them at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 No. I had to have interest in Labour you know when I startedwork you see because - the - it's li
ke a Labour movement is the - is the union as you may say. You had - you had to be in a union do you see and - that's Labour you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5600746 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 How did you spend your spare time now you were out at work - did you do different things from when you were at school
? Did you go out in the evening and where did you go to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 Go out - but me mother and father never knowed where - where we went to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5600746 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 Did they never ask you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 He asked us many a time but - we always had a alibi you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5600746 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 Did you never bring your friends home to meet your mum and dad?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 If we'd been out too long}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6710063\charrsid15163457  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 me mother'd come and have a look see where we are.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5600746 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 You'd got to be back at a special time had you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 We had to be in at - about half past eight for get ready for bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5600746 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 Did you make new friends when you went to work or were they your old friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 
There were some as we'd had at school. And there were some as had come from some other part do you see, but we all used congregate together and we used to - talk together on different things you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5600746 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 Did you go dancing or anything like that? Or cinemas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 
Oh used to go dancing. Oh aye, we - we used to go dancing. We used to go to school when there were a dance on you know. Aye, Daisy Hill school - they used - us
ed to have - dancing at Saturday night do you see, ah I think we - I think we had to pay sixpence for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5600746 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 It wasn't much was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5600746 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 In Westhoughton say someone did something that everybody disapproved of - did they have certain ways of tre
ating someone who did something wrong - do you remember anything like this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 Not in me young days. Not in me young days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5600746 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 Tell me what your memories are about your childhood then - tell me what your nicest memories are about childhood and your hom
e and Westhoughton? How you felt about your childhood and your mum and dad, looking back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 Well the best thing as we had were going on t' fair and riding on t' dobby horses you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5600746 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 This is your nicest memory?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 That - that was best time as we used to have.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5600746 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 What do you remember about your mum and dad especially though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 
I - I think as he - as they've learned us a lot. They - they learned us how to - how to speak and be civil and they've learned us to have our manners and they've they've also teached us from wrong - wrong from right and right from wrong.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5600746 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 What did they say was right and what did they say was wrong do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 Well it - it was wrong for you go and kick somebody if he'd done nothing to you. And that used
 to occur when you were - when you were like pals and somebody kicked your pal you know, and you'd go and intervene. They used to tell us for don't do that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5600746 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 But you had a happy childhood?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 Oh aye.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 You will hear where I cut the tape off. Mr
 Pilkington starts to say - I've had some bad times too, in his own words he said, I've had a harder time many a time worse than a camel going through the eye of a needle. I asked him what he meant by this and he got quite agitated and said, that there's 
not running? Meaning the tape of course. And I showed him it was switched off but he insisted I took the microphone away. He started to tell me then that this was concerned not with his home but with his marriage. I asked him when he was }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4872671 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457  and the onl
y thing that he could remember, he couldn't remember the date, he'd looked for his marriage lines from me being there the previous wee and couldn't find them. He told me he'd been }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4872671 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457  twice. The first time was shortly after he came home from the war. H
e thought it was about 1918 or the beginning of 1918. The bad times apparently had been with his first wife. He told me in rather diffiedent manner that she'd obviously been around with other men. He'd save money - he }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4872671 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457  rather late and spent quite a 
lot on her and bought her a fur coat and this seemed to get him quite agitated. q - She'd been good to him in many ways but he'd heard of her being out in this fur coat and having d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3165536\charrsid15163457 
rinks with another man. He'd qu}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 estioned her about this and her answer had b
een, well you prove it. He told me that for four years they'd never been out together and several of his mates as he put it, used to say to him, by gum, you'pre a fool. Staying in minding you children while she's out gallivanting - gallivanting of course 
m
eant enjoying herself. He told me she kept the house clean and was quite a good cook but he never had any peace of mind with her. And eventually when she died, he couldn't even remember the year she died, he remembered that she died of cancer, he met a po
liceman friend of his and this policeman said to him, by gum, Billie, you ought to throw cap into the air and not wait for it to come down - you should be pleased. By gum, Billie, she led these a bit of a dance lad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 Here again was the old problem of not wanting to discuss his }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4872671 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 
 life. Actually it didn't apply - his sons weren't born until well after 1920 and the wedding as far as he could remember wasn't until after 1918 but it was an illustration of how people seem reluctant to discuss their own }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4872671 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 
 life. He got quite agitated and said, I won't talk about this with that there on. He told me that he'd done a great deal of the job of bringing up the two boys. He'd had quite a great part in this. Although she was a good mother and seemed fond of 
them, but she couldn't bear to be in the house, she was always out and he told me that eventually he had found out the man that she was going with and meeting outside but he never could prove anything. Obviously this had been a very unhappy marriage.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 
I went on to ask him about his second marriage. He was very non-committal about this. Well her were all right, her were a god lass. But had died ten years ago. But he did tell me the romantic meeting that brought this marriage about. Apparently he met a f
riend of his in a pub and this friend had pointed this lady out who eventually became his second wife and in Mr Pilkngton's own words, this gentleman gave a quite high recommendation. He said, crl clogg age}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3165536\charrsid15163457 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 , thou know Billie, welts not gone. How how's tha
t for high Northern romance. I asked him what this actually meant. And he said that, well, you know, it - it's meaning back to nature you know. What my friend was trying to tel me was there was still able to have babbies - meaning babies of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 H
e was obviously very proud of his children, his two sons and on the third visit when I finished the tape he'd got a mild dose of flu and a very bad head and he was telling me both his sons had offered to give him a home. They'd been down at weekend and ta
k
en him to a wedding and of course I've got loads of songs, he had to do a couple of songs that he'd sung at the wedding for me. I think he would have put them on tape given the chance but I don't think they were very suitable. He said they were good boys,
 
very kind to him. He's a very nice old gentleman, full of life and quite high spirited. No teeth as usual, please where are the dentists in England because they never seem to fit the old gentlemen out. - that I interview. He was also very deaf which I mea
nt I had to keep using the pause key to repeat a question.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 
He asked me at the end of the interview what it was all about and what it was for. And of course I said, they'll be no names mentioned will there? I told no there wouldn't be and I tried to ex
plain what it was about and his comment was - oh I don't understand it - it's too clever for me. What were that there word again? So I wrote down sociology for him and I don't now whether this would mean anything at all.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 Like all the old people I ha
ve met he was very poor and he told me about how hard it was to make the pension bear them. How lonely it got and I got a cordial invitation to go back at any time and have a cup of tea. I can imagine some head scratching going on tonight at the old veter
a
ns club when he produces that paper with sociology on it. Very, very delightful person this old man but as you can hear from the tape he got quite agitated at times over some of the questions. He was very, very eager to please but wasn't quite sure of wha
t I wanted particularly on the question of the social set up of his days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4659335 RP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8394249\charrsid15163457 
As I was leaving the house the funniest thing happened. The old man said, wait a minute lass. And started to peep through the lace curtains. Then he went towards the door and op
ened the door and looked out. And he came back and said, they'll have seen that there car of thine at the door and they're a right nosy lot round here. They'll know it's not me home help day - and I just wanted to make sure before that went out that none 
o
f 'em were tooting. 'Tha's a nice lass and I wouldn't want 'em to get wrong impression. Totting of course means nosey. He'd been telling me earlier about a lady that one of the old veterans down at the club had been trying to get him fixed up with as he p
ut it. It took me all my time to say goodbye and keep my face straight. I kept remembering the remark his friend had made in the pub earlier but I refrained from making any comment. Obviously there's life in the old boy yet.
